04836nam a22007815i 9780231553100DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20202021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020015728  a97802315531007 a10.7312/defr199422doi  a(DE-B1597)566428  a(OCoLC)1159849782  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aQH75b.D3947 2021 4aQH75 7aNAT0100002bisacsh04a333.95/16223  aWT 1300qDE-162rvk0(DE-625)rvk/151932:1 aDeFries, Ruth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat Would Nature Do? :bA Guide for Our Uncertain Times /cRuth DeFries. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b19 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPrologue -- t1 The Dragons Are Back -- t2 Recovery from a Crash -- t3 Hedges for Bets -- t4 Mind the Net -- t5 One Size Fits No One -- t6 Cycles of Renewal -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNot long ago, the future seemed predictable. Now, certainty about the course of civilization has given way to fear and doubt. Raging fires, ravaging storms, political upheavals, financial collapse, and deadly pandemics lie ahead—or are already here. The world feels less comprehensible and more dangerous, and no one, from individuals to businesses and governments, knows how to navigate the path forward.Ruth DeFries argues that a surprising set of time-tested strategies from the natural world can help humanity weather these crises. Through trial and error over the eons, life has evolved astonishing and counterintuitive tricks in order to survive. DeFries details how a handful of fundamental strategies—investments in diversity, redundancy over efficiency, self-correcting feedbacks, and decisions based on bottom-up knowledge—enable life to persist through unpredictable, sudden shocks. Lessons for supply chains from a leaf’s intricate network of veins and stock market-saving “circuit breakers” patterned on planetary cycles reveal the power of these approaches for modern times. With humility and willingness to apply nature’s experience to our human-constructed world, DeFries demonstrates, we can withstand uncertain and perilous times. Exploring the lessons that life on Earth can teach us about coping with complexity, What Would Nature Do? offers timely options for civilization to reorganize for a safe and prosperous future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHuman ecology. 0aResilience (Ecology) 0aResilience (Ecology). 0aSustainability. 0aUncertainty. 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073907708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070480808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2020z9783110704600oZDB-23-DPM40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/defr1994240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231553100423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231553100/original  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070480-8  EBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-073907-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18